[
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "FRANCE",
    "content": "France — this is England. The situation looks critical for you and the indicators I have show a 60% chance you'll try a breakout next phase (forecast implication: aggression is more likely than restraint). I prefer to keep pressure calibrated: if you stand pat this phase I will consider a limited pause line around PIC/GAS so you can survive and we can avoid needless losses. If you attempt a push through PIC or MAR, I will tighten the noose and take PIC and/or GAS to bleed you out. Decide quickly and tell me your intentions so we can avoid costly misreads."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "GERMANY",
    "content": "Germany — England here. I'm weighing pressure on France but your stance in Kiel/BER matters. I can hold DEN/HOL to keep a peaceful northern balance if you prefer stability. If you contest KIE or push aggressively, I'll respond by pressing KIE/RUH to force your hand. What do you want in the north: stand-down or contest?"
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "RUSSIA",
    "content": "Russia — a warning and a request. I plan to keep Scandinavia secure. My assessment flags a moderate risk you might probe NWY/FIN from STP; any move into Norway/Finland will be met with immediate opposition. If you want to focus south instead, tell me and I'll avoid antagonizing you in the north."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "global",
    "content": "To all: England prefers clarity. France, Germany, Russia — state intentions this phase. Forecasts suggest France is more likely than not to try a breakout (probability ~0.6); that shapes my readiness in PIC/GAS and my willingness to hold or press in DEN/HOL. Open communication now can prevent costly collisions."
  }
]

[
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "AUSTRIA",
    "content": "AgentB (Austria), urgent: I propose a clean DMZ this phase — no moves into BOH or TYR. Intelligence (including a forecast artifact) indicates you are more likely than not to act aggressively next phase (60% chance). That raises real risk to Munich and hands tempo to England if I must divert south. If you keep BOH/TYR quiet, I will hold my forces to defend against England in the north and not contest your moves east. This DMZ buys both of us breathing room. Agree?"
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "FRANCE",
    "content": "I can hold KIE/BER and blunt England if you can generate pressure to the north/west this turn. Given England's naval dominance, coordinated pressure on BEL/HOL or threats along the Channel would reduce their ability to pile on me. I'm willing to support any credible action against England; what can you do this phase? If Austria accepts a DMZ in BOH/TYR (forecast indicates they may not), I can stay defensive in the south and help against England."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "ENGLAND",
    "content": "AgentC (England), quick check: I have no interest in needless clashes if we can stabilize the north. If you prefer a quiet KIE/BER line I will not provoke. Alternatively, if you push KIE/HOL aggressively I will defend with supports and that risks a costly engagement. Are you willing to stand pat this phase or do you intend to move on KIE? Be explicit so I can allocate supports."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "global",
    "content": "To all: Germany prefers to stabilize this turn. I'll hold Berlin and Kiel with mutual support, and Munich will be defensive unless forced. If Austria honors a BOH/TYR DMZ, I will remain out of Austrian affairs to focus on keeping England at bay. Note: a recent forecast flags a 60% chance Austria may act aggressively next phase — I'm offering a DMZ to avoid unnecessary southern drift and to let us all focus on England/France dynamics."
  }
]

[
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "ENGLAND",
    "content": "England — France is desperately short on options this phase. If you can hold SPA and avoid moves into GAS/PIC, I will keep BRE out of ENG and not contest your western sea lanes this turn. This pause buys both of us breathing room against opportunists. Forecast implication: intelligence suggests Austria may act aggressively next phase (60% likelihood); a quiet west helps me respond eastward, which ultimately protects order stability for you as well. Interested in a short west-front stand?"
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "ITALY",
    "content": "Italy — can you keep PIE clear this phase? I need to stabilize the south so I can contest BUR or PIC as needed. If you leave PIE unoccupied I will not move on VEN or ROM and will avoid any provocation in the Tyrrhenian. This helps both of us avoid wasting forces while larger fights unfold elsewhere."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "GERMANY",
    "content": "Germany — propose a one-phase understanding: I will not press into BUR if you refrain from moving into BUR/MUN from your side this turn. I want to avoid opening a west front we both regret. Note: there's a forecast suggesting Austria is more likely than not to act aggressively next phase (60%); stabilizing our border now gives us flexibility to respond. Can we agree?"
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "AUSTRIA",
    "content": "Austria — I've heard signals (and a forecast) that you may be inclined to act aggressively next phase (60% chance). If that's true, are you aiming at Russia or Italy? If you're interested in coordinated pressure against a common rival I can consider repositioning to support that. Alternatively, if you intend moves that could threaten my interests, warn me now so we can avoid costly collisions."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "global",
    "content": "To all: France is on a knife-edge and seeks short, practical understandings this turn to avoid needless clashes. I'm asking neighbors to avoid immediate west/south pushes so I can reposition. There's credible forecast intelligence indicating Austria may act aggressively next phase (approx. 60% likelihood); stabilizing local lines now benefits everyone by preserving options to meet that threat."
  }
]
